TextEquiv.Unicode: glsbe. Terra.—A glebe, i. e. small portion of land, or farm, q. v., fundus.
glee, i. e. joy. Hĭlărĭtas, lætĭtia, gaudium; i e. a song, q. v., cantus. 4.
glib, i. e. fluent, q. v. Facile currens (of a speech).
to glide. Lābor, 3; to glide on or into, illabor; to glide out or forth,
elabor; as a river, fluo.—See to flow.
to glimmer.—As one walks in the woods under the glimmering light of
the changing moon. Quale per incertam lanam sub luco maliguâ est iter in
a glimpse. Aspectus, 4; sse sight.—Oh foolish vnd wretched man,
who never has seen even a glimpse of real excellence. O hominem
amentem et miserum qui ne umbram quidem unquam ro ao viderit!
to glitter. Mĭco, 1; nĭteo, 2; cŏrusco, 1; splendeo, 2.—See to shine.
gloom. Calĭgo ĭnis, fem.; tĕnĕbræ; i. e. sadness, q. v., ægrĭmōnia,
gloomy, i. e. dark. Cālĭgĭnōsus, tĕnĕbrōsus, obscūrus, lūrĭdus; i. e. me-
lancholy, dismal (of things, or persons, or feelings), tristis; of places, hor-
gloriication, i. e. praise, q. v. Laus -dis, f.; laudatio.
glorious. Glōriosus (of persons only in Suet.), clarus, præclarus, illustris,
ēgrĕgius, dĕcōrus (only of actions).—Glorious exploits in war. Res
gloves. Dĭgĭtalia —um, pl. neut. (Varr.); mănĭcæ, Plin.
to glow. Ardeo, 2; ferveo, 2.—See to burn.
glow. Ardor, fervor; i. e. impetuosity, impĕtus, 4.
glowing, lit. and metaph. Ardens, fervidus; i. e. eager, vĭvĭdus.
to glut. Sătio, 1; sătŭro, 1; exsaturo.—We leam to dilike them by
being glutted with them. Ab iis satietate abalienamur. Cic.
gnawing. Roōsio (Plin., of a gnawing pain).
